We  talked yesterday about the somewhat strange=C2=A0possibility that publi=
c investors might be=C2=A0too=C2=A0focused on the long term. At a conferenc=
e in Saudi Arabia, Blackstone Group=E2=80=99s Steve Schwarzman and=C2=A0Bla=
ckRock Inc.=E2=80=99s Larry Fink both suggested that oil prices are high be=
cause investors have become so jazzed about funding a future transition to =
green energy that they are no longer willing to fund oil drilling. I wrote:=
One way to tell that story is that, influenced by Fink and others, investor=
s now insist on long-term sustainability. They believe that a zero-carbon w=
orld is coming, they want to invest in companies that will make money in a =
zero-carbon world, and they think that a lot of marginal oil drillers will =
not survive in that world. The oil drillers might agree! =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=
=99re gonna drill for oil for 10 years, sell it at $85 a barrel, make a lot=
 of money for our investors, and then close up shop when the world moves of=
f oil=E2=80=9D is a perfectly reasonable business plan. But =E2=80=94 Schwa=
rzman says =E2=80=94 investors will not finance it anymore, because they ar=
e myopically obsessed with the long run.[1]I also proposed some reasons tha=
t public-market investors might dislike=C2=A0businesses with good short-ter=
m cash flows but poor long-term prospects:The reason might be along the lin=
es of =E2=80=9Cpublic markets systematically undervalue the short-term cash=
 flows of dying businesses,=E2=80=9D or else =E2=80=9Cpublic-market investo=
rs require, or at least allow, corporate executives to do a big song and da=
nce about investing for the long run and pivoting to some sustainable busin=
ess model, so they won=E2=80=99t let a dying business just pay out its cash=
 to shareholders and die with dignity, but will instead demand that it squa=
nder that cash on doomed efforts to survive.=E2=80=9DI should emphasize: Al=
l this stuff is=C2=A0weird stuff. We have just come off a period of several=
 years in which people went around constantly complaining that public marke=
ts are too focused on the short term, that they undervalue long-term invest=
ment, that they care only about next quarter=E2=80=99s earnings. But I do t=
hink that we are in a different world now, one where public investors seem =
a bit  less interested in capital discipline and a bit more interested in t=
he far future.[2]A lot of this is captured by the term =E2=80=9CESG.=E2=80=
=9D Lots of investors now care about environmental, social and governance f=
actors; they consider those factors alongside more traditional financial me=
trics like how much money a company made last quarter. Part of the appeal o=
f ESG is that ultimate investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0the big asset managers=E2=
=80=99 customers =E2=80=94=C2=A0want to save the planet and so will pay a p=
remium for ESG investments. But another part of the appeal =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
nd the part that big asset managers  emphasize in their public statements =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0is that ESG investing is supposed to  get=C2=A0higher return=
s=C2=A0in the long run, because good-ESG businesses are  more sustainable t=
han bad-ESG businesses. If you pollute, you might make a lot of money now, =
but  eventually you=E2=80=99ll get in trouble; better to invest in business=
es that don=E2=80=99t pollute and that can continue making money forever.=
=C2=A0What does this mean for oil companies? For small independent oil and =
gas companies, I guess it means something like what Schwarzman said: It=E2=
=80=99s harder to get capital to fund your business, which is=C2=A0drilling=
 for oil and gas. But an integrated oil major is a different situation. A m=
odern integrated oil major isn=E2=80=99t going to say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99r=
e an oil company, we drill for oil and gas=E2=80=9D; it=E2=80=99s going to =
say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re an energy company, we work to build a sustainabl=
e energy future, we invest in solar and wind and biofuel initiatives,=E2=80=
=9D and then it will mumble under its breath =E2=80=9Cand drill for oil and=
 gas.=E2=80=9D Pumping oil and gas generates a lot of revenue =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0as do refining and pipeline and oil-trading businesses =E2=80=94=C2=A0wh=
ich the oil majors can use to invest in clean-energy projects.This has an o=
bvious appeal to investors. Many ESG-interested investors do not love oil-a=
nd-gas businesses, because they assume that those businesses will go away i=
n the long run and they care a lot about the long run. They do, however, lo=
ve sustainable-energy businesses, and the oil majors can build big well-cap=
italized sustainable-energy businesses. The oil majors can in some sense be=
 exactly what ESG investors want from oil companies: oil companies now, whe=
n oil is widely used, that will become not-oil companies later, when it is =
not.Still you could quibble. It is a little embarrassing for ESG-focused in=
vestors to buy oil companies at all, and integrated oil majors will general=
ly be so big and diversified that they=E2=80=99ll have a few especially emb=
arrassing projects, Arctic drilling or destructive spills or whatever. =E2=
=80=9CWe are a good ESG fund and we invest only in energy companies that ar=
e building a clean-energy future,=E2=80=9D an ESG fund can say, and then ac=
tivists will say =E2=80=9Cbut what about this oil spill that your favorite =
energy company just did,=E2=80=9D and the fund will have to be like =E2=80=
=9Cwell it=E2=80=99s a big company and the transition to clean energy will =
take time.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s somewhat unsatisfying.Meanwhile some inves=
tors are more old-school and like cash flows. They see the cash flows from =
oil drilling, which, in a world of $80 oil, are good. They think about Schw=
arzman=E2=80=99s complaint that ESG investing is pushing up the price of oi=
l, and they say: Well, great, then the cash flows from oil drilling should =
continue to be high. And then they see the oil majors spending those cash f=
lows on wind farms or whatever and they get a bit antsy. They say: No, we j=
ust want to bet on oil drilling being a good business. We want you to pump =
oil and sell it for a lot of money and give us those cash flows. Wind is gr=
eat and all but some other company can build wind farms; you=E2=80=99ve got=
 all this oil, which is valuable, so you should focus on that.A crude=C2=A0=
way to put it is that, when it comes to oil companies,=C2=A0a lot of big pu=
blic ESG-focused and ESG-curious investors care only about the long run, wh=
ile some other more opportunistic oil-focused investors care only about the=
 short run.If you=E2=80=99ve got one set of investors who care about one th=
ing and another set of investors who care about another thing, it is nice t=
o sell the first set of investors the thing they want and the second set of=
 investors the thing they want. And this happens: Big public oil companies =
sometimes sell their dirty assets, and their assets that will be stranded i=
n a world of stricter carbon regulation, to smaller private companies that =
are financed by investors who are less focused on ESG. The big companies ge=
t to be cleaner and more sustainable, which appeals to their investors. The=
 small companies buy good cash flows cheap, which appeals to their investor=
s, who are different.You could imagine  accelerating this approach:Activist=
 investor Dan Loeb has built a position in Royal Dutch Shell Plc and is pus=
hing for a breakup of the energy giant as it embraces renewable energy whil=
e continuing to pump oil and gas.Loeb=E2=80=99s Third Point LLC has taken a=
 $750 million stake, according to a person familiar with the matter, equiva=
lent to about 0.4% of the company. The firm said in a letter to investors W=
ednesday that Shell would benefit from breaking off its liquefied natural g=
as, renewables and marketing businesses into a standalone company. That wou=
ld separate it from Shell=E2=80=99s legacy energy business, which would inc=
lude the upstream, refining and chemicals operations.Here is Third Point=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0investor letter. Loeb describes Shell as a particularly=C2=A0g=
ood=C2=A0oil major from a sustainability perspective:Compared to its peers,=
 Shell generates a much larger percentage of its cash flow and earnings fro=
m stable businesses that have a major role to play in the energy transition=
. For example, Shell is the largest global player in liquified natural gas =
(=E2=80=9CLNG=E2=80=9D), which is a critical transition fuel to move off ca=
rbon intensive coal-fired power generation. In 2022, we expect the company=
=E2=80=99s energy transition businesses (LNG, Renewables and Marketing) to =
generate EBITDA of over $25 billion with sustaining capex of only $5 billio=
n. These businesses account for just over 40% of Shell=E2=80=99s EBITDA but=
 would likely support Shell=E2=80=99s entire enterprise value if they were =
a standalone company. At the current share price, we believe investors are =
getting the remaining ~60% of EBITDA (upstream, refining and chemicals) for=
 free.Management has been gradually divesting assets that are not aligned w=
ith a low-carbon future such as upstream and refining. This is perhaps most=
 evident in Shell=E2=80=99s refining business where the company went from o=
wning 54 refineries in 2004 to only five (by yearend.) This is a remarkable=
 accomplishment.=C2=A0Notice the claim that Shell=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cenergy=
 transition businesses =E2=80=A6=C2=A0account for just over 40% of Shell=E2=
=80=99s EBITDA but would likely support Shell=E2=80=99s entire enterprise v=
alue if they were a standalone company.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0That is, roughly spea=
king,=C2=A0a claim that modern public investors are so focused on sustainab=
le energy businesses that they value Shell=C2=A0only=C2=A0for its sustainab=
le businesses, and ascribe=C2=A0zero=C2=A0value to its (currently more lucr=
ative) oil-drilling-and-refining business.Well, if you think that a divisio=
n of a company is valued at zero by its current shareholders, you will prob=
ably propose separating out that division.=C2=A0Loeb goes on:=C2=A0In our v=
iew, Shell has too many competing stakeholders pushing it in too many diffe=
rent directions, resulting in an incoherent, conflicting set of strategies =
attempting to appease multiple interests but satisfying none. Some sharehol=
ders want Shell to invest aggressively in renewable energy. Other sharehold=
ers want it to prioritize return of capital and enjoy the exposure to legac=
y oil and gas. Some investors think Shell should shrink to grow, while we s=
uspect some within Shell seem sentimentally attached to its =E2=80=9Csuper =
major=E2=80=9D legacy. Some governments want Shell to decarbonize as rapidl=
y as possible. Other governments want it to continue to invest in oil and g=
as to keep energy prices affordable for consumers. Europe paradoxically wan=
ts both!Shell=E2=80=99s board and management have responded to this with in=
crementalism and attempts to =E2=80=9Cdo it all.=E2=80=9D As the saying goe=
s, you can=E2=80=99t be all things to all people. In trying to do so, Shell=
 has ended up with unhappy shareholders who have been starved of returns an=
d an unhappy society that wants to see Shell do more to decarbonize.=C2=A0H=
is solution would =E2=80=9Cinvolve the creation of multiple standalone comp=
anies,=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cmatch its business units with unique shareholde=
r constituencies who may be interested in different things (return of capit=
al vs. growth; legacy energy vs. energy transition)=E2=80=9D:For example, a=
 standalone legacy energy business (upstream, refining and chemicals) could=
 slow capex beyond what it has already promised, sell assets, and prioritiz=
e return of cash to=C2=A0shareholders (which can be reallocated by the mark=
et into low-carbon areas of the economy). A standalone LNG/Renewables/Marke=
ting business could combine modest cash returns with aggressive investment =
in renewables and other carbon reduction technologies (and this business wo=
uld benefit from a much lower cost of capital). Pursuing a bold strategy li=
ke this would likely lead to an acceleration of CO2 reduction as well as si=
gnificantly increased returns for shareholders, a win for all stakeholders.=
If you put the drilling-and-refining business into a pure drilling-and-refi=
ning company, with the=C2=A0explicit expectation=C2=A0that oil drilling and=
 refining will go away eventually, the drilling-and-refining company won=E2=
=80=99t feel any compulsion to spend money building for the future, and wil=
l just collect money from selling oil and distribute it to shareholders. It=
 will die a dignified and reasonable death as oil is phased out, and shareh=
olders will collect their cash and maybe invest it in green projects. And t=
he company will be run by oil people=C2=A0who are good at drilling oil effi=
ciently. (A good exercise is figuring out the right compensation scheme for=
 the executives of that company.)=C2=A0And somebody =E2=80=94=C2=A0hedge fu=
nds without much in the way of ESG branding, I guess =E2=80=94=C2=A0will bu=
y the stock, because the net present value of cash flows does=C2=A0set a fl=
oor under a stock price. If you can get a few years of reliable cash flows =
that you know won=E2=80=99t be squandered on hopeless pivots, you=E2=80=99l=
l pay something for them.Meanwhile if you put the sustainable-energy busine=
ss into a pure sustainable-energy company,=C2=A0it=C2=A0can invest lots of =
money in doing sustainable energy stuff, and if it needs more capital inves=
tors will be thrilled to give it some, because it will be a giant sustainab=
le-energy company that checks all of their ESG boxes. And it will have a hi=
gh stock price because it=E2=80=99s what modern, long-term-focused ESG inve=
stors want. (It will be worth as much as all of Shell is now, on Loeb=E2=80=
=99s math.) And the company will be run by=C2=A0sustainable-energy=C2=A0peo=
ple who care about the environment. The two=C2=A0companies will have differ=
ent goals, different investors, different managers.You could take the other=
 side of this. Shell does:[Shell Chief Executive Officer]=C2=A0Ben van Beur=
den said that the needs of Shell=E2=80=99s customers, and the company=E2=80=
=99s efforts to pivot away from fossil fuels, were better served by keeping=
 its range of assets and businesses. In particular, he said the company=E2=
=80=99s legacy oil-and-gas assets were needed to fund its investments in lo=
wer-carbon energy. ...On Thursday, Mr. van Beurden said he disagreed with t=
he notion that splitting up Shell would aid the energy transition or the co=
mpany.=E2=80=9CWe are able to do things with the collections of assets, bus=
iness models [and] customer-facing businesses that we have that is very har=
d to replicate if you were just [to] split up in a number of other companie=
s,=E2=80=9D he told reporters.=E2=80=9CA very significant part of this ener=
gy transition that we are talking about is going to be funded by the legacy=
 business,=E2=80=9D he added.Loeb=E2=80=99s basic mechanism here is: Take t=
he cash flows from legacy oil drilling, give them to shareholders, and let =
the shareholders invest them in clean energy if they want.=C2=A0Van Beurden=
=E2=80=99s is: Take the cash flows from legacy oil drilling and let=C2=A0hi=
m=C2=A0invest them in clean energy. In a sense this is the most traditional=
 of all activist conflicts: Should corporate managers be trusted to plan fo=
r the long term, or should they give money back to shareholders and let the=
 shareholders invest it elsewhere for the long term? Traditionally this con=
flict is about the financial value of the managers=E2=80=99 long-term plans=
. Now it=E2=80=99s also about=C2=A0who =E2=80=94=C2=A0oil-company executive=
s or hedge-fund managers =E2=80=94=C2=A0has a better=C2=A0plan for the worl=
d=E2=80=99s transition to clean energy.
