      Billionaire unrealized capital-gains tax
   =20
 =20
Look, on the one hand, I love a good  improbable tax proposal. On the other=
 hand I try not to write much about proposed legislation around here, becau=
se my assumption about bills is that they do not=C2=A0become laws,=C2=A0so =
why worry=C2=A0for no reason? There is a proposal=C2=A0in the U.S. Senate t=
o impose an annual tax on=C2=A0billionaires=E2=80=99 unrealized capital gai=
ns in public-market securities. Here is the proposed text. If you are an =
=E2=80=9Capplicable taxpayer=E2=80=9D (meaning income of $100 million per y=
ear or assets of $1 billion for three straight years), then you have to pay=
 capital-gains taxes on your publicly traded assets as though you sold them=
 at the end of each year.[3] If you own a bunch of public-company stock wit=
h a low basis =E2=80=94=C2=A0because you are say Mark Zuckerberg or Jeff Be=
zos or Warren Buffett =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you will have to pay a whole lot =
of taxes when this regime goes into effect (though you get five years to pa=
y the first bill), and then some more taxes every year that your stock goes=
 up.Here are criticisms of this plan from Aswath Damodaran (=E2=80=9CThe Bi=
llionaire Tax: The Worst Idea Ever?=E2=80=9D), Tyler Cowen, Noah Smith=C2=
=A0and  Alexis Leondis. Also it=E2=80=99s maybe unconstitutional to tax unr=
ealized income? People seem troubled by it. I am not troubled by it, becaus=
e bills do not become laws.The main thing to say about this proposal, from =
my perspective, is that it=C2=A0would=C2=A0create=C2=A0a truly joyful=C2=A0=
industry of public-market avoidance (take the=C2=A0company you founded priv=
ate, buy a private fund that wraps the S&P 500 in a confusing way, take the=
 company you founded public but retain a=C2=A0private promote or shares of =
an operating subsidiary rather than owning public shares yourself,=C2=A0etc=
.) and also=C2=A0billionaire-avoidance (keep $999 million and give the rest=
 to charity or your kids or a discreet trustee in the Cayman Islands, keep =
all of it in hard-to-value things and say they=E2=80=99re worth $999 millio=
n, etc.). I bet a lot of tax lawyers walked around with an extra spring in =
their step for the last couple of days: They were going to have=C2=A0so muc=
h fun=C2=A0and make=C2=A0so much money.=C2=A0Anyway the New York Times says=
 that =E2=80=9Cthe billionaires tax, officially unveiled early Wednesday mo=
rning, may have died before the ink was dry on its 107-page text,=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0because Joe Manchin doesn=E2=80=99t like it, as you kind of knew he w=
ouldn=E2=80=99t. Still. What fun we would have had.
