Why not:Cboe Global Markets, Inc. (Cboe: CBOE), a leading provider of globa=
l market infrastructure and tradable products, [yesterday] announced plans =
to launch Nanos by Cboe, a first of its kind options contract designed to s=
implify options trading. =C2=A0 Nanos by Cboe help make options trading acc=
essible for the everyday retail trader, allowing them to start small, learn=
 as they go and grow their trading confidence.Cboe plans to launch its firs=
t Nanos on the S&P 500 Index in first-quarter 2022. At a fraction of the si=
ze of a standard options contract, the one-multiplier, cash-settled Nanos S=
&P 500 contract answers the growing demand for a simpler, cost-effective wa=
y to gain broad exposure to the U.S. equity market. At 1/100th the size of =
an XSP1 option, the Mini-S&P 500 Index options contract, Nanos S&P 500 (tic=
ker symbol: NANOS) help simplify the process of trading options, letting tr=
aders focus on understanding the market and refining their trading strategi=
es.The website describes some of the simplifications, including =E2=80=9C1-=
multiplier with short-term expiration date=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CLimited st=
rikes, easier decision-making.=E2=80=9D Just, like, you can put down a buck=
 or two=C2=A0to bet that the S&P 500 will end the week above 4,600, and if =
you=E2=80=99re right and it closes at 4,605 then you get $5, if it closes a=
t 4,650 you get $50, etc.[5] That seems like a reasonable gamble that some =
people might like. You can=E2=80=99t say that if you=E2=80=99re CBOE, thoug=
h, so you have to talk about =E2=80=9Ceducation=E2=80=9D:"Our goal with Nan=
os is to use education to inspire and empower new market participants to pu=
rsue a sustainable financial future. We believe Nanos are more appropriatel=
y sized for retail traders and enable traders to better express their opini=
ons on market movements at a comparatively lower premium price," said Ed Ti=
lly, Chairman, President and CEO of Cboe Global Markets. "Through our Nanos=
 S&P 500 product, we are broadening access to a greater universe of traders=
 who can enjoy the potential benefits options provide, including hedging, a=
sset allocation and income generation strategies."Oh yes hedging, lots of b=
uy-and-hold retail investors=C2=A0need weekly-expiry S&P options for hedgin=
g.=C2=A0I really cannot stress enough how different the last, like, three y=
ears have been from  what I expected. My bet three years ago was that norma=
l people were going to become=C2=A0less=C2=A0interested in investing, that =
robo-advisers and indexing would let people automate their investing and sp=
end their time doing something more interesting. Instead, investing has bec=
ome way more interesting.I feel like a popular story a few years ago was so=
mething like: =E2=80=9CAs stock investing has become more boring and straig=
htforward and everyone just indexes, people who want a wild gamble have mov=
ed into crypto.=E2=80=9D Like, the rise of indexing created some vast resid=
ue of unsatisfied yearning for excitement, and that yearning was satisfied =
by buying Bitcoin. Now I think a reasonable story might be =E2=80=9Cas cryp=
to has attracted billions of dollars of investor capital because it is fun =
and exciting, the traditional financial system is falling all over itself t=
o be fun and exciting to compete.=E2=80=9D If you are launching an index fu=
nd in 2021 it had better be a meme-stock index fund, or a crypto index fund=
. Nobody wants boring stability anymore.
