MTEwMjgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbfedeb46" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> eventually you=E2=80=99ll get in trouble</a>; better to invest in =
businesses that don=E2=80=99t pollute and that can continue making money fo=
rever.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What does this mean for oil co=
mpanies? For small independent oil and gas companies, I guess it means some=
thing like what Schwarzman said: It=E2=80=99s harder to get capital to fund=
 your business, which is=C2=A0drilling for oil and gas. But an integrated o=
il major is a different situation. A modern integrated oil major isn=E2=80=
=99t going to say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re an oil company, we drill for oil a=
nd gas=E2=80=9D; it=E2=80=99s going to say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re an energy=
 company, we work to build a sustainable energy future, we invest in solar =
and wind and biofuel initiatives,=E2=80=9D and then it will mumble under it=
s breath =E2=80=9Cand drill for oil and gas.=E2=80=9D Pumping oil and gas g=
enerates a lot of revenue =E2=80=94=C2=A0as do refining and pipeline and oi=
l-trading businesses =E2=80=94=C2=A0which the oil majors can use to invest =
in clean-energy projects.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This has an obvio=
us appeal to investors. Many ESG-interested investors do not love oil-and-g=
as businesses, because they assume that those businesses will go away in th=
e long run and they care a lot about the long run. They do, however, love s=
ustainable-energy businesses, and the oil majors can build big well-capital=
ized sustainable-energy businesses. The oil majors can in some sense be exa=
ctly what ESG investors want from oil companies: oil companies now, when oi=
l is widely used, that will become not-oil companies later, when it is not.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still you could quibble. It is a little em=
barrassing for ESG-focused investors to buy oil companies at all, and integ=
rated oil majors will generally be so big and diversified that they=E2=80=
=99ll have a few especially embarrassing projects, <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25498985.267682/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaGlnaG5vcn=
RobmV3cy5jb20vZW4vc2hlbGwtcGxhbnMtcmVzdW1lLW9mZnNob3JlLW9pbC1hbmQtZ2FzLWV4c=
GxvcmF0aW9uLWFyY3RpYy1hbGFza2E/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB62a901e9" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
Arctic drilling</a> or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/25498985.267682/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmJjLmNvbS9uZXdzL3dvcmxkLWFmcmljYS01NT=
g1MzAyNA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcb9b5cda" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">destructive spills</a> =
or whatever. =E2=80=9CWe are a good ESG fund and we invest only in energy c=
ompanies that are building a clean-energy future,=E2=80=9D an ESG fund can =
say, and then activists will say =E2=80=9Cbut what about this oil spill tha=
t your favorite energy company just did,=E2=80=9D and the fund will have to=
 be like =E2=80=9Cwell it=E2=80=99s a big company and the transition to cle=
an energy will take time.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s somewhat unsatisfying.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile some investors are more old-school an=
d like cash flows. They see the cash flows from oil drilling, which, in a w=
orld of $80 oil, are good. They think about Schwarzman=E2=80=99s complaint =
that ESG investing is pushing up the price of oil, and they say: Well, grea=
t, then the cash flows from oil drilling should continue to be high. And th=
en they see the oil majors spending those cash flows on wind farms or whate=
ver and they get a bit antsy. They say: No, we just want to bet on oil dril=
ling being a good business. We want you to pump oil and sell it for a lot o=
f money and give us those cash flows. Wind is great and all but some other =
company can build wind farms; you=E2=80=99ve got all this oil, which is val=
uable, so you should focus on that.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A crude=
=C2=A0way to put it is that, when it comes to oil companies,=C2=A0a lot of =
big public ESG-focused and ESG-curious investors care only about the long r=
un, while some other more opportunistic oil-focused investors care only abo=
ut the short run.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you=E2=80=99ve got one=
 set of investors who care about one thing and another set of investors who=
 care about another thing, it is nice to sell the first set of investors th=
e thing they want and the second set of investors the thing they want. And =
this happens: Big public oil companies sometimes <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25498985.267682/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2Nv=
bnRlbnQvNGRlZTcwODAtM2ExYi00NzlmLWE1MGMtYzM2NDFjODJjMTQy/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB66314d77" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">sell their dirty assets</a>, and their assets that=
 will be stranded in a world of stricter carbon regulation, to smaller priv=
ate companies that are financed by investors who are less focused on ESG. T=
he big companies get to be cleaner and more sustainable, which appeals to t=
heir investors. The small companies buy good cash flows cheap, which appeal=
s to their investors, who are different.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yo=
u could imagine <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25=
498985.267682/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtM=
TAtMjcvYWN0aXZpc3QtbG9lYi10YWtlcy1zaGVsbC1zdGFrZS1hbmQtcHVzaGVzLWZvci1hLWJy=
ZWFrLXVwP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjgyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3N=
vdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTAyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB522088ec" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> accelerating this approach</a>=
:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Activist investor Dan Loeb ha=
s built a position in Royal Dutch Shell Plc and is pushing for a breakup of=
 the energy giant as it embraces renewable energy while continuing to pump =
oil and gas.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Loeb=E2=80=99s Third Point LLC=
 has taken a $750 million stake, according to a person familiar with the ma=
tter, equivalent to about 0.4% of the company. The firm said in a letter to=
 investors Wednesday that Shell would benefit from breaking off its liquefi=
ed natural gas, renewables and marketing businesses into a standalone compa=
ny. That would separate it from Shell=E2=80=99s legacy energy business, whi=
ch would include the upstream, refining and chemicals operations.</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/25498985.267682/aHR0cHM6Ly90aGlyZHBvaW50bGltaXRlZ=
C5jb20vd3AtY29udGVudC91cGxvYWRzLzIwMjEvMTAvVGhpcmQtUG9pbnQtUTMtMjAyMS1JbnZl=
c3Rvci1MZXR0ZXItVFBJTC5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6864dd52" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Thir=
d Point=E2=80=99s=C2=A0investor letter</a>. Loeb describes Shell as a parti=
cularly=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>oil major from a sustainability perspective=
:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Compared to its peers, Shell =
generates a much larger percentage of its cash flow and earnings from stabl=
e businesses that have a major role to play in the energy transition. For e=
xample, Shell is the largest global player in liquified natural gas (=E2=80=
=9CLNG=E2=80=9D), which is a critical transition fuel to move off carbon in=
tensive coal-fired power generation. In 2022, we expect the company=E2=80=
=99s energy transition businesses (LNG, Renewables and Marketing) to genera=
te EBITDA of over $25 billion with sustaining capex of only $5 billion. The=
se businesses account for just over 40% of Shell=E2=80=99s EBITDA but would=
 likely support Shell=E2=80=99s entire enterprise value if they were a stan=
dalone company. At the current share price, we believe investors are gettin=
g the remaining ~60% of EBITDA (upstream, refining and chemicals) for free.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Management has been gradually divesting as=
sets that are not aligned with a low-carbon future such as upstream and ref=
ining. This is perhaps most evident in Shell=E2=80=99s refining business wh=
ere the company went from owning 54 refineries in 2004 to only five (by yea=
rend.) This is a remarkable accomplishment.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Notice the claim that Shell=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cenergy =
transition businesses =E2=80=A6=C2=A0account for just over 40% of Shell=E2=
=80=99s EBITDA but would likely support Shell=E2=80=99s entire enterprise v=
alue if they were a standalone company.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0That is, roughly spea=
king,=C2=A0a claim that modern public investors are so focused on sustainab=
le energy businesses that they value Shell=C2=A0<em>only=C2=A0</em>for its =
sustainable businesses, and ascribe=C2=A0<em>zero=C2=A0</em>value to its (c=
urrently more lucrative) oil-drilling-and-refining business.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Well, if you think that a division of a company is valued=
 at zero by its current shareholders, you will probably propose separating =
out that division.=C2=A0Loeb goes on:=C2=A0</p><blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">In our view, Shell has too many competing stakeholders pushing=
 it in too many different directions, resulting in an incoherent, conflicti=
ng set of strategies attempting to appease multiple interests but satisfyin=
g none. Some shareholders want Shell to invest aggressively in renewable en=
ergy. Other shareholders want it to prioritize return of capital and enjoy =
the exposure to legacy oil and gas. Some investors think Shell should shrin=
k to grow, while we suspect some within Shell seem sentimentally attached t=
o its =E2=80=9Csuper major=E2=80=9D legacy. Some governments want Shell to =
decarbonize as rapidly as possible. Other governments want it to continue t=
o invest in oil and gas to keep energy prices affordable for consumers. Eur=
ope paradoxically wants both!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Shell=E2=80=
=99s board and management have responded to this with incrementalism and at=
tempts to =E2=80=9Cdo it all.=E2=80=9D As the saying goes, you can=E2=80=99=
t be all things to all people. In trying to do so, Shell has ended up with =
unhappy shareholders who have been starved of returns and an unhappy societ=
y that wants to see Shell do more to decarbonize.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">His solution would =E2=80=9Cinvolve the creation =
of multiple standalone companies,=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cmatch its business u=
nits with unique shareholder constituencies who may be interested in differ=
ent things (return of capital vs. growth; legacy energy vs. energy transiti=
on)=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For example, a st=
andalone legacy energy business (upstream, refining and chemicals) could sl=
ow capex beyond what it has already promised, sell assets, and prioritize r=
eturn of cash to=C2=A0shareholders (which can be reallocated by the market =
into low-carbon areas of the economy). A standalone LNG/Renewables/Marketin=
g business could combine modest cash returns with aggressive investment in =
renewables and other carbon reduction technologies (and this business would=
 benefit from a much lower cost of capital). Pursuing a bold strategy like =
this would likely lead to an acceleration of CO2 reduction as well as signi=
ficantly increased returns for shareholders, a win for all stakeholders.</p=
></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you put the drilling-and-refi=
ning business into a pure drilling-and-refining company, with the=C2=A0<em>=
explicit expectation=C2=A0</em>that oil drilling and refining will <em>go a=
way</em> eventually, the drilling-and-refining company won=E2=80=99t feel a=
ny compulsion to spend money building for the future, and will just collect=
 money from selling oil and distribute it to shareholders. It will die a di=
gnified and reasonable death as oil is phased out, and shareholders will co=
llect their cash and maybe invest it in green projects. And the company wil=
l be run by <em>oil people=C2=A0</em>who are good at drilling oil efficient=
ly. (A good exercise is figuring out the right compensation scheme for the =
executives of that company.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And some=
body =E2=80=94=C2=A0hedge funds without much in the way of ESG branding, I =
guess =E2=80=94=C2=A0will buy the stock, because the net present value of c=
ash flows does=C2=A0set a floor under a stock price. If you can get a few y=
ears of reliable cash flows that you know won=E2=80=99t be squandered on ho=
peless pivots, you=E2=80=99ll pay something for them.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Meanwhile if you put the sustainable-energy business into a pure=
 sustainable-energy company,=C2=A0<em>it=C2=A0</em>can invest lots of money=
 in doing sustainable energy stuff, and if it needs more capital investors =
will be thrilled to give it some, because it will be a giant sustainable-en=
ergy company that checks all of their ESG boxes. And it will have a high st=
ock price because it=E2=80=99s what modern, long-term-focused ESG investors=
 want. (It will be worth as much as all of Shell is now, on Loeb=E2=80=99s =
math.) And the company will be run by=C2=A0<em>sustainable-energy=C2=A0peop=
le</em> who care about the environment. The two=C2=A0companies will have di=
fferent goals, different investors, different managers.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">You could take the other side of this. <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25498985.267682/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvb=
S9hcnRpY2xlcy9zaGVsbC1haW1zLXRvLWhhbHZlLWNhcmJvbi1lbWlzc2lvbnMtYnktMjAzMC1h=
cy1hY3RpdmlzdC1jYWxscy1mb3ItYnJlYWt1cC0xMTYzNTQwOTc1MD9tb2Q9aHBfbGVhZF9wb3M=
2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7dc0f852" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Shell does</a>:</p><blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Shell Chief Executive Officer]=C2=A0Ben van =
Beurden said that the needs of Shell=E2=80=99s customers, and the company=
=E2=80=99s efforts to pivot away from fossil fuels, were better served by k=
eeping its range of assets and businesses. In particular, he said the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s legacy oil-and-gas assets were needed to fund its investments =
in lower-carbon energy. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Thursday, Mr=
. van Beurden said he disagreed with the notion that splitting up Shell wou=
ld aid the energy transition or the company.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">=E2=80=9CWe are able to do things with the collections of assets, busines=
s models [and] customer-facing businesses that we have that is very hard to=
 replicate if you were just [to] split up in a number of other companies,=
=E2=80=9D he told reporters.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CA ver=
y significant part of this energy transition that we are talking about is g=
oing to be funded by the legacy business,=E2=80=9D he added.</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Loeb=E2=80=99s basic mechanism here is: Take=
 the cash flows from legacy oil drilling, give them to shareholders, and le=
t the shareholders invest them in clean energy if they want.=C2=A0Van Beurd=
en=E2=80=99s is: Take the cash flows from legacy oil drilling and let=C2=A0=
<em>him=C2=A0</em>invest them in clean energy. In a sense this is the most =
traditional of all activist conflicts: Should corporate managers be trusted=
 to plan for the long term, or should they give money back to shareholders =
and let the shareholders invest it elsewhere for the long term? Traditional=
ly this conflict is about the financial value of the managers=E2=80=99 long=
-term plans. Now it=E2=80=99s also about=C2=A0who =E2=80=94=C2=A0oil-compan=
y executives or hedge-fund managers =E2=80=94=C2=A0has a better=C2=A0plan f=
or the world=E2=80=99s transition to clean energy.</p><table class=3D"livei=
